# Protect all your most important internet accounts using this one weird trick (hackers HATE it): An overview of computers and cybersecurity

So, bad news. 

## Your private information has already leaked onto the internet.

Yep\! All of it.  
But it’s not your fault. There’s nothing you could have done.  
Your data could have been leaked by [a company you’ve never heard of or used](https://www.twingate.com/blog/tips/experian-data-breach), or even one of their [subcontractors](https://www.politico.com/news/2025/02/25/irs-contractor-leaked-hundreds-of-thousands-of-returns-00205980).  
Data leaks can lead to [identity theft](https://www.identitytheft.gov/Steps), regular money theft, unauthorized use of your Netflix account or anything in between.

Also:

## Your computer is going to break

This one you’re looking at right now\! Its days are numbered.   
This is a problem because they are expensive and you pretty much need one to function in society.  
When it breaks, you’ll need to buy a new machine and find some way to regain access to all the files and data you had on the old one.

## On no!

If it makes you feel better, you’re not alone. Everyone else is in the same boat\!  
In that way, the internet is kind of a big game of “you don’t have to be faster than the bear, you have to be faster than the guy next to you.”   
With enough motivation and resources, it’s possible to steal anybody’s data. If your data is a little more annoying to use, maybe an attacker will go after someone else. 

There is always a trade-off between security and convenience.   
If it is too inconvenient to deal with a security measure, people will eventually give up on it.   
The goal is to get the *most* security for each unit of inconvenience you introduce. What are the biggest “bang for the buck” things you can do, etc.

This document goes over most of the major technology pieces and describes how they fit together.   
It also tries to summarize “philosophies” or “mentalities” that many tech professionals adopt when thinking about security. 

## Super disclaimer

I’m not any kind of security expert.   
The views in this document are my own opinions, informational in nature, and based on my novice understanding of the subjects.  
Use at your own risk.

# Terms and tools

A brief overview of the terms and tools you hear thrown around.   
Feel free to skip this section unless you’re interested.

## Software

Software is hard to build. As a consumer of software, it’s important to remember that every time you use software, you are explicitly trusting the humans who produced it. 
All software is produced by humans to perform "the task they intend."

“Free” software is probably not free, because humans don’t usually do hard work for free.   
They are making their money somehow, and it’s usually by having a different *intention* for the software than what was advertised.   
It may be that you downloaded a free app that claims to “prevent spyware,” but the real intent of the software is to collect and sell data about you. 

There’s nothing inherently wrong with that business model – your data is great. Everyone wants it\!  

Later on in this doc, we'll discuss ways to give your critical data to sofware to try to keep it safe.
Just like when selecting a bank, you should be careful when selecting software that you intend to use to protect your data. One way to be careful is to understand how the company makes money.

## Devices

#### Laptops

Laptops are built to be carried around until you drop them or put coffee on them or lose them.   
Their average lifespan is shorter than desktops.  
As-of this writing, [Consumer Reports’ most reliable laptop](https://www.consumerreports.org/electronics-computers/laptops-chromebooks/buying-guide/) comes with a [1y factory warranty](https://www.apple.com/support/products/mac/#:~:text=Every%20Mac%20comes%20with%20one,accidental%20damage%2C%20plus%20applicable%20tax.).
In a big IT department, a typical plan is to buy the warranty for 3 years, then *see* if you can get the machine to make it through a 4th before replacement ([1](https://www.reddit.com/r/sysadmin/comments/1g9k9gu/how_long_are_your_laptop_lifecycles/)).

Without qualification: **Critical data should not exist *only* on a laptop. Just like phones, laptops are *disposable.***

#### Desktops

A desktop may last 3 to 10 years before parts start to fail, starting with the things that move, recharge or get hot ([1](https://www.hp.com/us-en/shop/tech-takes/average-computer-lifespan#:~:text=Average%20desktop%20lifespan%3A%203%20to,Less%20risk%20of%20physical%20damage), [2](https://www.consumerreports.org/electronics-computers/laptops-chromebooks/laptopreliability-a7029273631/)).  
Desktops do not have to be tiny, so their parts are bigger, typically cheaper, and operate cooler than comparable laptop parts. 

From a data recovery perspective, the worst thing to fail is the disk drive  
As a pro tip, with desktops you should use a “two disk drives” strategy.

* Keep your operating system and programs on one “replaceable” disk  
  * This is the “totally destroyable disk that doesn’t matter” disk	  
  * Do not put any personal documents on this one.  
  * If it fails, it only costs money to replace.  
  * If you need to reinstall the operating system, or burn everything down and start over, this will be relatively painless  
* Keep your personal data files (including documents folders) on a separate disk.  
  * Here’s [one way to do it on windows](https://www.windowscentral.com/how-move-default-user-folders-new-drive-windows-10)  
  * Even better, keep them backed up with a cloud storage product, Apple iCloud, Google Drive, Microsoft OneDrive are great options for redundancy.

#### Phones and Tablets

See “laptops” above, but even more so.   
Because of the way phones fit into the authentication story below, if you’re not very careful, phones can easily become a [single point of failure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_point_of_failure).   
Losing a critical phone may make it difficult or impossible to regain access to accounts. 

## Authentication (a.k.a. “two-factor auth”, 2FA or MFA)

[Authentication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Authentication) is the process of verifying that someone’s identity claim is true (e.g. whether your driver's license is genuine).  
[Multi-Factor Authentication](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-factor_authentication) (MFA) is a technique used to verify an identity claim.   
It adds an extra layer of security by requiring users to provide two or more “verification factors” as evidence.   
These factors can include:

* Something only you **know**: A password or PIN.  
* Something only you **have**: A physical token, smartphone, or security key.  
* Something only you **are**: Biometrics such as fingerprints, facial recognition, or DNA.

As an attacker, there's a certain amount of work required to steal a password, physical key, phone, or email account.   
Stealing *another* factor for the *same* user account is much harder.   
However as a user, you already have all of those things and it's not *that* much more annoying to use two of them instead of one.  
This asymmetry between the small annoyance incurred by having to use two factors versus the large difficulty incurred by the need to steal multiple factors is the reason the system works.

### Authentication factor technologies

Almost any second factor will do the job.   
This is the list of “best” auth factors, ranked from most secure to least

1. Passkeys, Security Keys, "hardware keys" (Apple)  
2. Authenticators (one-time-passwords)(Microsoft Authenticator, One-time-passwords, Google Authenticator)  
3. Email Verification (code sent over email)  
4. SMS (code sent over text message)  
5. Username \+ Password / shared secret (these can be brute forced or overheard) 

### Passwords

A password is something that “you know,” and hopefully something that only a few people are supposed to know – a “shared secret.”  
To a computer system, “knowing” this secret is evidence that you are who you say you are.

Passwords are a good example of the trade-off between security and usability.
A strong password is typically long, complex and unique, making it difficult for attackers to guess or crack.   
However, such passwords can be challenging for humans to actually remember and manage.
Research has shown that strict password-composition policies, such as requiring a mix of uppercase letters, numbers, and special characters, do not necessarily lead to better security outcomes.   
Instead, these policies can lead to user frustration and poor password practices, such as writing passwords down or reusing them across multiple accounts ([interesting paper on the topic](https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~fms27/papers/2015-BonneauHerOorSta-passwords--author.pdf)).

My favorite anecdote about passwords is the ancient [story of Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ali_Baba_and_the_Forty_Thieves).   
Ali Baba overhearing the password "open sesame" was all it took to defeat the 40 thieves' entire security system!   
If they had required the password *in addition* to having the right physical key (a second form of auth) they might have kept their treasure. 

Passwords are weak against many kinds of inexpensive attacks (meaning they don’t take long or cost much to execute)

1. They are guessable  
   1. Many users create passwords that are easy to remember, but also easy for attackers to guess. Common examples include "password123," "123456," or "qwerty." Weak passwords are highly vulnerable to brute force attacks and dictionary attacks.  
   2. You can also use automated software to try all possible password combinations until the correct one is found. EG: “aaa”, “aab”, “aac”, etc until you get through them all. Longer and more complex passwords make brute force attacks more challenging.  
2. They are reused  
   1. People often reuse the same password across multiple accounts. If one account is compromised in a data breach, attackers can use the stolen credentials to access other accounts that share the same password. This practice significantly increases the risk of multiple accounts being compromised.  
   2. “Credential stuffing attacks” occur when attackers use automated tools to test stolen username and password combinations across multiple websites. This works because humans tend to pick similar passwords and then use them multiple times.   
3. You can be tricked into giving them away (“phishing attacks”)  
   1. Phishing attacks involve tricking users into revealing their passwords by pretending to be a legitimate entity, such as a bank or an online service. These attacks can be carried out through email, fake websites, or other deceptive means, leading to stolen credentials.  
   2. “Social engineering attacks” are techniques used to trick individuals into divulging their passwords. This can include impersonating trusted individuals or creating scenarios that pressure users into revealing their credentials.  
      This is a pretty common way for even computer security experts to be hacked.   
4. They can be stolen (or overheard\!)  
   1. If passwords are not stored securely, they can be easily compromised. Storing passwords in plaintext, using weak hashing algorithms, or improper handling of password data can lead to significant security breaches.  
   2. Without a proper password management system, users may struggle to remember multiple complex passwords. This often leads to poor practices, such as writing passwords down or saving them in insecure locations  
   3. Malicious programs installed on your computer may be tracking the letters you type on your keyboard.  
      This is a pretty common way for even computer security experts to be hacked. 

### Security keys

A security key is “something you ‘have’”.   
They are usually cards or a USB key-looking thing (like a [YubiKey](https://www.yubico.com/products/how-the-yubikey-works/)).

The basic idea is that no two of them are the same and the part that makes it unique can never leave the device.   
Instead of you, the client, sending along your username and password to a server, the server sends *you* a little piece of data.   
Your device modifies the data using its uniqueness, and then you send back the result.   
If the result checks out, then the server knows that whoever you are, you must at least have the little key. 

The strength and weakness of security keys is that they are irreplaceable and almost unforgeable.   
If you lose it, you literally cannot replace it or recover it. 

In this document, I recommend using them rarely, and when you do, use at least two. 

Compared to passwords, hardware security keys are extremely resistant to phishing, keylogging and man-in-the-middle attacks but infinity percent more likely to fall out of a pocket or be eaten by a pet.

If you’re interested in the math, there are only a few main techniques but they have a bunch of names.  
A few videos might help you build a mental model of how they work:

* RSA [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pq8gNbvfaoM](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Pq8gNbvfaoM)  
* [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman\_key\_exchange](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange)

### Passkeys

Passkeys are “something that you have.”  
They’re called “passKEYS” I think because they were designed to replace “passWORDS?”

They operate a lot like security keys but they are transferable to other devices.  
For example, [Apple Passkeys](https://support.apple.com/en-us/102195) are stored in the iCloud Keychain which is synced automatically across all your Apple devices.   
Instead of needing a single physical key, you can login to any device with access to your iCloud keychain.

Passkeys are only as secure as the login technology of the device (like face id or fingerprints).   
Just like security keys, they are resistant to phishing, but you leave your fingerprints everywhere, etc.

Great overview: https://www.passkeys.io/technical-details  
I wish all my technical questions had such great websites to explain them to me\!

### Software-based One Time Password (“OTP”) Tokens

There are a lot of authenticator apps that all work the same: 

* Google authenticator  
* Microsoft authenticator  
* 1Password  
* YubiKeys / https://www.yubico.com/products/yubico-authenticator/

When you register your device to be an OTP token generator, you create and share a secret (like a long password) between your device and the server.   
You can verify that both you and the server have the same secret by doing some math that uses the key and some measure of the current time (like [seconds since 1970](https://www.unixtimestamp.com/)).  
The result is a 6-digit number that you can safely send across the internet.   
You’re unlikely to guess that exact number unless you have access to the shared secret.   
Unlike Security Keys where the secret never leaves the device, you can easily migrate the shared secret to other devices. 

This form of auth is only as secure as the device it’s stored on.   
For example, if you use the 1Password OTP feature, it’s not really a “second” form of auth from regular passwords – if you have access to the 1Password vault, you have access to both the password and the OTP token generator. 

### Text messages (SMS)

These are better than NO second factor, but they are worse than all the others.   
The basic idea is that there is only one of your phone, so if I send a text message to that number, whoever gets it must be you\!

This should work in theory, except telecommunication companies need to keep it relatively easy to transfer your number to their network from a competitor’s.   
This makes phone-number-based auth factors vulnerable to [SIM swapping scams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SIM_swap_scam) where an attacker is able to transfer your number to a new phone.   
That said, SMS is better than literally nothing, so definitely do enable it if it’s the only supported MFA option.

## Password managers 

A password manager is a tool that remembers your secrets. Sometimes called a “password vault.”

This could be: 

* Your own frail human memory  
* A sticky note on your monitor  
* [Elaborate tattoos?](https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/memento)  
* A part of your web browser  
* Specialized piece of software

Good features to look for include: 

* Generates passwords that humans cannot remember.   
* Works on all your devices.  
* Only unlockable by you.  
* Requires MFA to access.  
* Built by a company that is incentivized to protect your information. A good sign is when the company posts [Bug Bounties](https://hackerone.com/1password?type=team) and will pay security researchers (“bounty hunters” or “[white-hat hackers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_hat_\(computer_security\))” if you will) “enough” money that they would rather report the bugs they find rather than using the bug to steal.
* Used by large enterprises ("What does Microsoft use for this?" is the right kind of question).
* Ability to share access to data with other users (without having to share your master password)

It’s generally better to use a standalone application from a dedicated company over one embedded into your browser. Browser-based solutions are sometimes harder to migrate and don't always work as well in non-web applications.

[Wirecutter has a few recommendations](https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/reviews/best-password-managers/):

* 1password  
* bitwarden  
* lastpass

## Browsers and extensions

A web browser asks for files from someone else’s computer.   
The other computer will send back some code it thinks you should run, and the location and names of other files it thinks you’ll need to “render the page.”   
Your browser will do what it is asked and transforms that text information into all the pictures and images you associate with websites.   
Often though, the owner of the other computer may send you code and images (like ads for instance) that you don’t actually *want* to run on your computer.   
No thanks, stranger on the internet\!

Browser *extensions* are powerful.   
By definition they are allowed to change the content of a webpage while it’s being rendered.   
Ad blockers are able to dynamically decide *not* to render parts of the page, or not to run certain code it was sent by the other computer. 

Because they are so powerful, you should only install extensions that you trust.   
Unfortunately, a lot of them are malicious themselves. In addition to whatever they claim to do, they also install some spyware or steal data.   
I recommend you install as few as possible and keep them updated like your other pieces of critical software. 

In fact, I recommend installing exactly 2: an ad blocker and the extension for your password manager. 

### Ad blockers

There are a bunch of good reasons to block ads on the internet.   
Ads have to be downloaded like other page content (so they consume time and bandwidth), but more importantly they can track your internet activity and execute scripts in your browser.  
I recommend paying for the services you use and blocking all the ads you can. 

* [uBlock origin](https://ublockorigin.com/), open source software   
* [Privacy badger](https://privacybadger.org/#What-is-Privacy-Badger) is sponsored by the EFF

### Password management extensions

This is part of the convenience / security trade off.   
1password, lastpass, bitwarden extensions are usually considered safe to install (make sure you install them from the browsers’ extension store), but the real threats are really *other* malicious browser extensions or websites masquerading as your bank or something in order to trick your password manager’s “autofill” feature.  
There is not a perfect recommendation here. If you trust all your other extensions, then using an extension to fill in password information is valuable – it helps avoid things like [typosquatting](https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/topic/what-is-typosquatting-54a18872-8459-4d47-b3e3-d84d9a362eb0#:~:text=Typosquatting%20is%20what%20we%20call,the%20missing%20%22s%22\).) and avoids putting your password into the “clipboard” (the copy / paste buffer) which is readable from any app on your device. 

### HTTPS / Encrypted communication

For backwards compatibility reasons, sometimes websites still let you connect via the old “http” (not “s”) url.  
The [“s” in “https” stands for “secure”](https://aws.amazon.com/compare/the-difference-between-https-and-http/) and you should always, always prefer it.  
It used to be necessary to install an extension to force this preference, but most modern browsers now support automatically switching to the HTTPS version of a site.   
Consumer reports has a great guide on the topic: [install https everywhere](https://securityplanner.consumerreports.org/tool/install-https-everywhere). 

# Habits and approaches / Preparing for the worst

You cannot remove all risk, so make a plan to recover from a future disaster.   
A great read on this topic is [https://how.complexsystems.fail/](https://how.complexsystems.fail/)

### Use a password manager

* Computers are good at remembering any password, so use dedicated password manager software, see above!

### Keep your software and operating systems up to date

* Whenever a new vulnerability is found in a piece of software, a race begins\!   
  * [Publishing and fixing the vulnerability](https://nvd.nist.gov/general/cve-process) takes [time](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/vulnerability-management-lifecycle), and so does testing and convincing your customers to actually install the update when it’s ready.   
  * Meanwhile, attackers are using it as fast as they can\!  
* Enable automatic updates on [all your devices](https://www.nytimes.com/wirecutter/guides/online-security-enable-automatic-updates/).   
* Click those little yellow “update” buttons in your browser\!  
* [https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/device-security-guidance/managing-deployed-devices/keeping-devices-and-software-up-to-date](https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/device-security-guidance/managing-deployed-devices/keeping-devices-and-software-up-to-date)

### Reduce blast radius

Consider how bad the situation would be if various pieces fail.

How much damage could be caused when:

* A single password is stolen?  
* A password vault is stolen?  
* A phone is broken?  
* A phone is hacked?  
* A family member’s phone is hacked?

### Reduce “time to recovery”

How long would it take you to recover when:

* A single password is stolen?  
* A password vault is stolen?  
* A phone is broken?  
* A phone is hacked?  
* A family member’s phone is hacked?

### Redundancy, redundancy, redundancy

Websites are also made out of computers which break all the time. 
So how do big companies build a reliable system out of unreliable parts? 
In short, they do so by building systems that are resilient against certain amounts of failure through the use of redundant parts.

The basic logic goes like this:

1. Complex systems are built out of parts.
2. Every part will definitely fail *some*day.  
3. Parts are generally made well, so it’s unlikely that a given part will fail on a given day.
4. It is even more unlikely that two *independent* parts would fail on the *same* day.
5. Therefore, all you need is for every part to have a plan for recovering from partial failure.

For our discussion, let's say you have a digital photograph that you don't want to lose.
The standard way to do this is to always have copies of the file on two different drives.
When one drive fails, you won't have lost any data, but you'll be down to having your data backed up on only one drive.
You should urgently aim to replace the broken drive and return to your target status of always having copies of the files on two different drives.

You can definitely do this yourself using multiple disk drives ([example](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_RAID_levels#RAID_1)), and it’s also the fundamental idea behind “highly available” cloud storage products like google drive or amazon photos.   
In those sorts of products, when you upload a file it’s copied 3-5  times *per [data center](https://wp.technologyreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/googlecbf009-11.jpg)* (a massive room full of hard drives), and then it’s copied again to 2-3 *other* data centers located in *other* parts of the country.   
With that level of redundancy, even when a single data center experiences a catastrophe, they can quickly (usually within minutes) route you over to a healthy data center somewhere else that already has a perfect backup of your files.   
This gives them the time they need to repair the data center and minimal data is lost.

# Getting started

It's never too late to start making good choices.
These are probably the right ideas in approximately the right order.

1. Start using a password manager  
   1. Install the password manager on all your devices  
   2. Secure your password manager   
      1. This should be your *most secure* thing. Put most of your effort here.  
      2. [Use a strong, memorable password](https://bitwarden.com/blog/picking-the-right-password-for-your-password-manager/).  
      3. Use a strong second factor (consider using a security key)  
      4. Use a strong *third* factor (sometimes called a [setup key](https://support.1password.com/secret-key/?mac)) – print it out and store it in a safe.  
2. Move your passwords to the manager.   
   1. Change all your weak passwords  
   2. Use strong, randomly generated passwords (or passkeys if available\!)  
3. Enable MFA on all accounts you can  
   1. Especially for email, banking, bill paying, and social media  
   2. Use authenticator apps like Microsoft Authenticator, Google Authenticator, or 1Password  
   3. Avoid using SMS wherever possible.  
4. Secure your important accounts  
   1. Important accounts are those that either:  
      1. Access money?  
      2. Are used to reset passwords for accounts that access money  
      3. This includes your email account and the “recovery email account” listed as the account recovery   
   2. This should be your *second-most secure* thing. Put a lot of your effort here.  
   3. Require and use a strong second factor (OTP or security key, not email or SMS)  
   4. Try logging into your email account from an [incognito tab](https://support.google.com/chrome/answer/95464?hl=en&co=GENIE.Platform%3DDesktop#).   
5. Secure your mobile phone number PIN
6. Build an emergency recovery kit
